  "answer": "**This specific narrative—describing a lotus-born creator weighing divine śrāddha-vegetables against a jackfruit (panasa), finding the jackfruit slightly heavier, and then establishing numerical equivalences for eggplant (bṛhatī) as three hundred, ginger (ārdraka) as six hundred, and sesame (tila) as one hundred (together equaling a thousand vegetables for ancestral satisfaction)—does not appear in the Falsafa corpus.**\n\nExtensive searches using distinctive phrases and terms from the query (e.g., \"jackfruit\", \"panasa\", \"lotus-born\", \"scale-pan\", \"śrāddha-vegetables\", \"eggplant ginger sesame\", \"three hundred\" with vegetables/ancestors, etc.) across the English translations returned zero results. The corpus's 37 works, including relevant Smṛti texts like *Manusmṛti*, *Parāśara Smṛti*, *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, *Kātyāyana Smṛti*, *Yama Smṛti*, *Aṅgirasa Smṛti*, and *Bṛhaspati Smṛti* (which cover dharmaśāstra topics such as rituals and ancestral offerings), do not contain this passage or matching content. Not every topic from classical Indic literature is covered in the current corpus.",
